{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.1,0.15,0.25,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11126"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43662"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with six weeks of amenorrhoea and three days of light vaginal bleeding. She has a medical history of two previous caesarean sections and takes no regular medications. She appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Speculum examination reveals a closed cervical os with minimal dark blood in the vaginal vault.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum beta human chorionic gonadotropin (bHCG) is 12,400 IU/L (0-5). Transvaginal ultrasound shows an empty endometrial cavity with normal endometrial thickness. A 6-week gestational sac containing a yolk sac and 2.3 mm foetal pole is visualised in the anterior aspect of the lower uterine segment. The myometrium between the gestational sac and the bladder measures 2 mm in thickness. Colour Doppler demonstrates increased vascularity surrounding the gestational sac. Cardiac activity is present with a foetal heart rate of 145 beats/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caesarean scar ectopic pregnancy","Cervical ectopic pregnancy","Threatened miscarriage","Low implantation intrauterine pregnancy","Cornual ectopic pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and ultrasound findings consistent with a caesarean scar ectopic pregnancy. The key diagnostic features include a history of previous caesarean sections, positive pregnancy test, empty uterine cavity, and a gestational sac implanted at the site of the previous caesarean scar in the anterior lower uterine segment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaesarean scar ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when a blastocyst implants into the myometrial defect of a previous caesarean section scar. The incidence is increasing with the rising caesarean section rate worldwide. Transvaginal ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosis, with key features including an empty uterine cavity, gestational sac located anteriorly at the level of the internal os in the site of the previous caesarean section scar, and thin or absent myometrium between the gestational sac and bladder. This condition carries significant risks including uterine rupture, life-threatening haemorrhage, and loss of future fertility if not diagnosed and managed appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E involves implantation of the gestational sac in the endocervical canal. While it can present similarly with vaginal bleeding and a positive pregnancy test, on ultrasound the gestational sac would be located within the cervical canal below the level of the internal os, with the uterine cavity empty. The hourglass shape of the uterus with ballooning of the cervix is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThreatened miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E presents with vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy but with an intrauterine gestational sac. The ultrasound would show a normally implanted pregnancy in the uterine cavity, not in the caesarean scar. The cervical os is closed, and the pregnancy may continue normally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow implantation intrauterine pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a pregnancy that implants in the lower uterine segment but within the endometrial cavity. Unlike a caesarean scar pregnancy, there would be endometrium rather than myometrium between the gestational sac and the bladder, and the gestational sac would be within the uterine cavity, not in the myometrial defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECornual ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to implantation in the interstitial portion of the fallopian tube as it enters the uterine cornua. On ultrasound, the gestational sac would be eccentrically located in the upper lateral aspect of the uterus, surrounded by a thin layer of myometrium. This differs from the lower anterior location seen in caesarean scar pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Caesarean scar ectopic pregnancy is characterised by implantation of a gestational sac in the myometrial defect of a previous caesarean section scar.","Transvaginal ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing a caesarean scar ectopic pregnancy.","Key diagnostic features include an empty uterine cavity, gestational sac implanted in the anterior lower uterine segment at the site of previous caesarean scar, and thin or absent myometrium between the gestational sac and bladder."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 21). BJOG. 2016;123(13):e15\u2013e55. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1111/1471-0528.14189","Elson CJ, Salim R, Potdar N, Chetty M, Ross JA, Kirk EJ on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy. BJOG 2016;. 123: e15\u2013e55. Available from: https://obgyn.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/1471-0528.14189","Queensland Clinical Guidelines. Early pregnancy loss. Guideline No. MN22.29-V7-R27 Queensland Health. 2022. Available from: http://www.health.qld.gov.au/qcg"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76137"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T10:42:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T13:40:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,